LII. 1. Brachioflmninz' objecto eos excludit. A brachium in military language means any outwork, whether a build- ing or a ditch. Here the meaning is, that Hannibal, by means of some work (probably a ditch) thrown between the camp and the stream, shut the Romans out from the river. Many editions have flumine, and change the order of the words to brachio objecto, flumine eos excludit. If flumini be retained, it must be taken after objecto.

3. pacti...acceperunt. The order of this sentence is very much involved. It seems to be “pacti (sc. Romani) ut arma atque equos traderent, et ut eo pretio persoluto (nempe) in capita Romana trecenis nummis quadrigatis‚ in socios ducenis, in servos centenis, cum singulis abirent vestimentis, in castra hostes acceperunt.''
